- The "key to the top-performing observatory" refers to the unique identifier of the telescope with the best performance score; 
- "Sharpness of its eyes in viewing the sky" refers to the telescope's average magnitude error, where lower values indicate better performance; 
- "Master stargazer" refers to the user with the highest access count; 
- "Unlocking the secrets of the universe" refers to accessing observations in the access logs.

In astronomy, the magnitude scale is a logarithmic scale used to measure the brightness of celestial objects. A lower magnitude indicates a brighter object; 
A Modified Julian Date (MJD) is the number of days since midnight on November 17, 1858, in the Gregorian calendar; 
For this database, the Modified Julian Dates 59580 and 59585 may correspond to specific dates in the Gregorian calendar.

